This paper is likely to belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category as it discusses the use of a Dirichlet prior for learning belief networks. It may also belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category as Bayesian networks are commonly used in AI. The paper also involves information theory (cs.IT) as it characterizes the Dirichlet distribution. Additionally, it may be relevant to the data structures (cs.DS) sub-category as it deals with the representation of belief networks. Finally, it could be relevant to the statistics (cs.ST) sub-category as it involves statistical modeling.
